(III) Choose $x_1, x_2 \in (0,1)$, $x_1 < x_2$ so that the peak interval determined by (I) is either $(0,x_2)$ or $(x_1,1)$. Within the obtained peak interval, choose $x_3$ such that $x_3$ with $x_1$ or $x_3$ with $x_2$ similarly determines a new peak interval. In the case where the first determined peak interval is $(0,x_2)$, try to determine the values of $x_1, x_2, x_3$ such that the absolute difference between any two of them is not less than $0.02$ and the length of the new peak interval is shortened to $0.34$.  
(The length of an interval equals the difference between its right and left endpoints.)

