Let the price of a pen be $p$ cents and the price of a pencil be $q$ cents. We form the following system of equations:
\begin{align*}
6p + 2q &= 348, \\
3p + 4q &= 234.
\end{align*}

To solve the system, first, multiply the first equation by 2 to make elimination of $p$ more straightforward:
\begin{align*}
12p + 4q &= 696, \\
3p + 4q &= 234.
\end{align*}

Subtract the second equation from the first:
\begin{align*}
(12p + 4q) - (3p + 4q) &= 696 - 234, \\
9p &= 462, \\
p &= \frac{462}{9}, \\
p &= 51.
\end{align*}

Therefore, the cost of a pen is $\boxed{51}$ cents.

